# Supabase Migration Plan

This document outlines the steps to migrate the architecture from Firebase Auth and PostgreSQL to a unified Supabase stack. It assumes that the Supabase project is already created, user data has been migrated, and environment variables are set in Railway.

## Phase 1: Database Schema Updates
We will update the `schema.sql` file so you can run it on the existing Supabase Postgres database.

### [MODIFY] [schema.sql](file:///Users/navesarussi/KC/kc-monorepo/apps/api/src/database/schema.sql)
- Add a proper Foreign Key linking `user_profiles.id` to Supabase's internal `auth.users(id)` for cascading deletes.
- Ensure **Row Level Security (RLS)** is enabled on all tables, and configure appropriate policies so that only the Backend (Service Role) can bypass RLS, securing the DB from public internet access.
- Add a Postgres Trigger to automatically insert a new row in `user_profiles` when a user signs up.

## Phase 2: Backend Components (`apps/api`)
We will replace Firebase Admin with Supabase and point the Postgres pool to Supabase's Postgres.

### [MODIFY] [package.json](file:///Users/navesarussi/KC/kc-monorepo/apps/api/package.json)
- Add `@supabase/supabase-js`.
- Remove `firebase-admin`.

### [DELETE] [firebase-admin.service.ts](file:///Users/navesarussi/KC/kc-monorepo/apps/api/src/auth/firebase-admin.service.ts)
- Delete the Firebase Admin service.

### [NEW] [supabase.service.ts](file:///Users/navesarussi/KC/kc-monorepo/apps/api/src/auth/supabase.service.ts)
- Create a service to initialize the Supabase Admin client and provide token verification utilities using the `SUPABASE_JWT_SECRET`.

### [MODIFY] [jwt-auth.guard.ts](file:///Users/navesarussi/KC/kc-monorepo/apps/api/src/auth/jwt-auth.guard.ts)
- Replace Firebase token verification with Supabase token verification.
- Update the database query to match `user_profiles.id` with the Supabase `auth.users.id`.

## Phase 3: Frontend Components (`apps/mobile`)
We will replace the Firebase JS SDK with the Supabase JS SDK.

### [MODIFY] [package.json](file:///Users/navesarussi/KC/kc-monorepo/apps/mobile/package.json)
- Add `@supabase/supabase-js`.
- Remove `firebase`.

### [DELETE] [firebaseClient.ts](file:///Users/navesarussi/KC/kc-monorepo/apps/mobile/utils/firebaseClient.ts)
- Delete the Firebase client initialization.

### [NEW] [supabaseClient.ts](file:///Users/navesarussi/KC/kc-monorepo/apps/mobile/utils/supabaseClient.ts)
- Initialize the Supabase client using `EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL` and `EXPO_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY`.
- Configure it to use `@react-native-async-storage/async-storage` for robust session persistence.

### [MODIFY] [authService.ts](file:///Users/navesarussi/KC/kc-monorepo/apps/mobile/utils/authService.ts)
- Rewrite authentication flows (`signUpWithEmail`, `signInWithEmail`, `signOut`, `sendPasswordReset`, etc.) to use `supabase.auth`.

### [MODIFY] [FirebaseGoogleButton.tsx](file:///Users/navesarussi/KC/kc-monorepo/apps/mobile/components/FirebaseGoogleButton.tsx)
- Rename to `GoogleLoginButton.tsx` and implement Supabase Google OAuth flow.

### [MODIFY] [app.json](file:///Users/navesarussi/KC/kc-monorepo/apps/mobile/app.json)
- Ensure **Deep Linking** (URL Schemes) is correctly configured so the user is redirected back to the app after the browser OAuth flow.

### [MODIFY] [apiService.ts](file:///Users/navesarussi/KC/kc-monorepo/apps/mobile/utils/apiService.ts)
- Update the token retrieval logic to get the session token from Supabase Auth instead of Firebase Auth.

## Verification Plan

### Automated Tests
- Run `npm run lint` and `npm run test` in both `api` and `mobile` to ensure no Firebase references remain and compilation succeeds.

### Manual Verification
1. Open the mobile app (Expo) and perform a sign-up with a new email and password.
2. Verify the Postgres trigger automatically creates a `user_profiles` row for the new user.
3. Perform a login and verify the app successfully receives a Supabase JWT.
4. Make an authenticated API request to the backend and ensure `JwtAuthGuard` successfully decodes the token and matches the user in the database.
